							<div class="article" style="border-bottom: 5px solid #00205c;">
								
								
								
	
								<a id="a6a00d8341c4eab53ef0264e2ead1f1200d"></a>
							
								
								<h3><a href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/discounts-for-fractional-ownership-of-artwork.html"><strong><em>Discounts For Fractional Ownership Of Artwork</em></strong></a></h3>
								
								
								<div class="line">
									<p class="author"> By <a href="#">Paul Caron</a></p>
									
									<div class="share hidden-phone">
										<a href="#"><i class="icon-share"></i> Share</a>
										<div class="dropdown clearfix">
											<div class="tab-arrow"></div>
											<ul class="clearfix">
												<li><a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/discounts-for-fractional-ownership-of-artwork.html"><i class="icon-facebook"></i></a></li>
												<li><a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/discounts-for-fractional-ownership-of-artwork.html&text=<strong><em>Discounts For Fractional Ownership Of Artwork</em></strong>&via=SoCalTaxProf"><i class="icon-twitter"></i></a></li>
												<li><a href="https://plus.google.com/share?url=https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/discounts-for-fractional-ownership-of-artwork.html"><i class="icon-google-plus"></i></a></li>
												<li><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/shareArticle?mini=true&url=https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/discounts-for-fractional-ownership-of-artwork.html"><i class="icon-linkedin"></i></a></li>
												<li><a href="mailto:?subject=<strong><em>Discounts For Fractional Ownership Of Artwork</em></strong> on The Taxprof Blog&body=Check this article out on The Taxprof Blog: https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/discounts-for-fractional-ownership-of-artwork.html"><i class="icon-envelope"></i></a></li>
											</ul>
										</div>
									</div>
	
								</div>
	
								<div class="hidden-phone">
	
									<p style="text-align: justify;">Maren N. Eisenmesser (J.D. 2020, Brooklyn), Note, <a href="https://brooklynworks.brooklaw.edu/bjcfcl/vol14/iss1/8/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Discounts for Fractional Ownership of Real Property Are Accepted, So Why Haven&#39;t the IRS and Courts Accepted Discounts for Fractional Ownership of Artwork?</a>, 14 Brook. J. Corp. Fin. &amp; Com. L. 75 (2019):</p>
<p style="margin: 15px 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px none; outline: 0px none; font-size: 14px; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: #ebf0f3; line-height: 20px; color: #363636; font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;">In 2014, the <a href="https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-5th-circuit/1678153.html" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Fifth Circuit held</a> that Mr. Elkins’s estate was entitled to apply a fractional ownership discount to determine the taxable value of the undivided interest in artwork. The estate received a $14 million refund plus interest. The Internal Revenue Code directs taxpayers to value the items in a gross estate at their fair market value. Fractional ownership adds another problem in the valuation of an estate’s interest property. In general, courts have accepted fractional ownership discounts for real property. In contrast, courts have been reluctant to apply a fractional ownership discount for artwork.</p>

									
									<p><a class="btn btn-small" href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/discounts-for-fractional-ownership-of-artwork.html#more">Continue reading <i class="icon-double-angle-right"></i></a></p>
	
									
									
