								<a id="a6a00d8341c4eab53ef026bde8e4013200c"></a>
							
								
								<h3><a href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/shanske-how-the-states-can-tax-shifted-corporate-profits.html"><strong>Shanske: <em> How The States Can Tax Shifted Corporate Profits</em></strong></a></h3>
								
								
								<div class="line">
									<p class="author"> By <a href="#">Paul Caron</a></p>
									
									<div class="share hidden-phone">
										<a href="#"><i class="icon-share"></i> Share</a>
										<div class="dropdown clearfix">
											<div class="tab-arrow"></div>
											<ul class="clearfix">
												<li><a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/shanske-how-the-states-can-tax-shifted-corporate-profits.html"><i class="icon-facebook"></i></a></li>
												<li><a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/shanske-how-the-states-can-tax-shifted-corporate-profits.html&text=<strong>Shanske: <em> How The States Can Tax Shifted Corporate Profits</em></strong>&via=SoCalTaxProf"><i class="icon-twitter"></i></a></li>
												<li><a href="https://plus.google.com/share?url=https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/shanske-how-the-states-can-tax-shifted-corporate-profits.html"><i class="icon-google-plus"></i></a></li>
												<li><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/shareArticle?mini=true&url=https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/shanske-how-the-states-can-tax-shifted-corporate-profits.html"><i class="icon-linkedin"></i></a></li>
												<li><a href="mailto:?subject=<strong>Shanske: <em> How The States Can Tax Shifted Corporate Profits</em></strong> on The Taxprof Blog&body=Check this article out on The Taxprof Blog: https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/shanske-how-the-states-can-tax-shifted-corporate-profits.html"><i class="icon-envelope"></i></a></li>
											</ul>
										</div>
									</div>
	
								</div>
	
								<div class="hidden-phone">
	
									<p style="text-align: justify;">Darien Shanske (UC-Davis), <a href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3679356" rel="noopener" target="_blank">How the States Can Tax Shifted Corporate Profits: An Application of Strategic Conformity</a>, 93 S. Cal. L. Rev. ___ (2020):</p>
<p style="margin: 15px 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px none; outline: 0px none; font-size: 14px; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: #ebf0f3; line-height: 20px; color: #363636; font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;">The combination of pandemic, recession and federal dysfunction has put severe fiscal strain on the states. Given the scale of the crisis and the essential nature of the services now being cut, it would be reasonable for states to contemplate inefficient — and even regressive — revenue-raising measures. Yet surely they should not start with such measures. They should start with making the efficient and progressive improvements to their revenue systems that they should have made anyway.</p>
<p style="margin: 15px 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px none; outline: 0px none; font-size: 14px; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: #ebf0f3; line-height: 20px; color: #363636; font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;">Improving the taxation of the profits of multinational corporations — the topic of this Article — represents a reform that would be efficient, progressive and relatively straightforward to administer. Not only would such a reform thus represent good tax policy, but it would raise significant revenue. And, if substantial revenue, efficiency, progressivity and administrability are not sufficiently motivating, then I will also add that it would be particularly appropriate to make these changes during the pandemic so as to raise revenue from those best able to pay during the current crisis.</p>

									
									<p><a class="btn btn-small" href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/shanske-how-the-states-can-tax-shifted-corporate-profits.html#more">Continue reading <i class="icon-double-angle-right"></i></a></p>
	
									
									
									<p class="posted">
									September  1, 2020 in <a href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/scholarship/">Scholarship</a>, <a href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/tax/">Tax</a>, <a href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/tax-scholarship/">Tax Scholarship</a>  | <a href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/shanske-how-the-states-can-tax-shifted-corporate-profits.html">Permalink</a>
									
									| <a href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/09/shanske-how-the-states-can-tax-shifted-corporate-profits.html#comments">Comments (1)</a>
									
									
									</p>
									
