								<h3><a href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/08/weisbach-the-trade-off-between-tax-administration-and-tax-compliance.html"><strong>Weisbach: <em> The Trade-Off Between Tax Administration And Tax Compliance</em></strong></a></h3>
								
								
								<div class="line">
									<p class="author"> By <a href="#">Paul Caron</a></p>
									
									<div class="share hidden-phone">
										<a href="#"><i class="icon-share"></i> Share</a>
										<div class="dropdown clearfix">
											<div class="tab-arrow"></div>
											<ul class="clearfix">
												<li><a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/08/weisbach-the-trade-off-between-tax-administration-and-tax-compliance.html"><i class="icon-facebook"></i></a></li>
												<li><a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/08/weisbach-the-trade-off-between-tax-administration-and-tax-compliance.html&text=<strong>Weisbach: <em> The Trade-Off Between Tax Administration And Tax Compliance</em></strong>&via=SoCalTaxProf"><i class="icon-twitter"></i></a></li>
												<li><a href="https://plus.google.com/share?url=https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/08/weisbach-the-trade-off-between-tax-administration-and-tax-compliance.html"><i class="icon-google-plus"></i></a></li>
												<li><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/shareArticle?mini=true&url=https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/08/weisbach-the-trade-off-between-tax-administration-and-tax-compliance.html"><i class="icon-linkedin"></i></a></li>
												<li><a href="mailto:?subject=<strong>Weisbach: <em> The Trade-Off Between Tax Administration And Tax Compliance</em></strong> on The Taxprof Blog&body=Check this article out on The Taxprof Blog: https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/08/weisbach-the-trade-off-between-tax-administration-and-tax-compliance.html"><i class="icon-envelope"></i></a></li>
											</ul>
										</div>
									</div>
	
								</div>
	
								<div class="hidden-phone">
	
									<p style="text-align: justify;">David A. Weisbach (Chicago), <a href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3680827" rel="noopener" target="_blank">The Trade-Off Between Tax Administration and Tax Compliance</a>:</p>
<p style="margin: 15px 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px none; outline: 0px none; font-size: 14px; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: #ebf0f3; line-height: 20px; color: #363636; font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; word-spacing: 0px;">This paper revisits optimal tax enforcement policy, focusing on two elements of that policy: (1) the optimal mix of government-level tax administration and individual-level tax compliance; and (2) the optimal mix of this combination (together, tax enforcement) and tax rates. The standard view is that we should weight tax administration but not tax compliance by the government’s cost of funds because we must pay for tax administration, but not compliance, through distorting taxes. As a result, we might want to rely on tax compliance measures even when using tax administration would otherwise be less expensive. Using a ﬂexible model that allows the costs of tax ad-ministration and compliance to be imposed in arbitrary ways, I ﬁnd instead that we should choose between administration and compliance costs purely on eﬀectiveness grounds, without weighting.</p>

									
									<p><a class="btn btn-small" href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/08/weisbach-the-trade-off-between-tax-administration-and-tax-compliance.html#more">Continue reading <i class="icon-double-angle-right"></i></a></p>
	
									
									
									<p class="posted">
									August 31, 2020 in <a href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/scholarship/">Scholarship</a>, <a href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/tax/">Tax</a>, <a href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/tax-scholarship/">Tax Scholarship</a>  | <a href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/08/weisbach-the-trade-off-between-tax-administration-and-tax-compliance.html">Permalink</a>
									
									| <a href="https://taxprof.typepad.com/taxprof_blog/2020/08/weisbach-the-trade-off-between-tax-administration-and-tax-compliance.html#comments">Comments (0)</a>
									
									
									</p>
									
